  "prompt": "How does a fluorescent light work?",
  "response": "A fluorescent light works through several key steps:\n\n1. Electric Current\n- An electric current passes through a gas-filled glass tube\n\n2. Gas Mixture\n- The tube contains mercury vapor and an inert gas like argon\n\n3. Electron Excitation\n- When electricity flows, it energizes the mercury vapor\n- Mercury atoms become excited and release ultraviolet (UV) light\n\n4. Phosphor Coating\n- The inside of the tube is coated with phosphor\n- When UV light hits the phosphor, it causes the phosphor to glow\n- This phosphor coating converts UV light into visible white or colored light\n\n5. Ballast\n- A ballast regulates the electrical current\n- It provides the initial high voltage to start the lamp\n- Then it limits the current to maintain steady light output\n\n6. Electrodes\n- Metal electrodes at each end of the tube help start and sustain the electrical discharge\n\nCompared to incandescent bulbs, fluorescent lights are more energy-efficient because they convert more electrical energy into light and less into heat.\n\nModern versions include compact fluorescent lamps (CFLs) and linear tube lights used in offices, schools, and other large spaces.",
